excerpt: 1600s fort complex with 3 buildings, including a mosque, containing paintings, antiques & weapons.
detail_description: Lalbagh Fort, a 17th-century Mughal fort complex in Old Dhaka, Bangladesh, was initiated in 1678 by Subahdar Muhammad Shah. The incomplete yet impressive structure comprises three main buildings: a mosque, a tomb, and an audience hall. The fort's architecture reflects the grandeur of Mughal rule with its minarets and domes.
name: Lalbagh Fort

excerpt: Built in the 12th century, this Sena-style Hindu temple is considered Bangladesh's National Temple.
detail_description: Dhakeshwari National Temple, a Sena-style Hindu temple, is Bangladesh's National Temple and a significant historical landmark in Dhaka. Legend has it that King Ballal Sen was inspired to build the temple after finding a buried statue of the Goddess Durga in the jungle, as revealed in one of his dreams. The present structure may be modern, but there has been a temple on this site for nine centuries.
name: Dhakeshwari National Temple

excerpt: Large national museum with exhibits tracing the history, culture, art & archaeology of Bangladesh.
detail_description: The Bangladesh National Museum is a significant institution that showcases the rich history, culture, art, and archaeology of Bangladesh. It offers a diverse range of exhibits that trace the country's heritage and global connections. The museum's Department of Contemporary Art and World Civilisation features seven galleries displaying paintings, sculptures, and tapestries representing contemporary Bangladeshi art as well as artefacts from various civilizations worldwide. This department also houses works by notable artists such as Quamrul Hassan and S.M.
name: Bangladesh National Museum

excerpt: Popular museum with a modern design exhibiting the history of the Bangladesh Liberation War of 1971.
detail_description: The Liberation War Museum, situated in Segunbagicha, is a modern museum that pays tribute to the Bangladesh Liberation War of 1971. It houses a diverse collection of artifacts, educational materials, and images depicting the conflict and its aftermath, including the refugee crisis that resulted in millions fleeing their homes. The museum offers a compelling glimpse into this tumultuous period through graphic displays and a poignant assortment of mementos honoring those who perished during the war.
name: Liberation War Museum
address: Civic Centre, Plot : F11/A & F11/B, Dhaka 1207, Bangladesh

detail_description: Curzon Hall, located within the University of Dhaka, is a stunning example of Indo-Saracenic architecture that captivates visitors with its historical significance and beauty. Originally established as a town hall in 1904 under British rule and named after Lord Curzon, this architectural gem now serves as an academic hub for the Faculty of Sciences. Beyond its educational role, Curzon Hall played a pivotal part in Bangladesh's independence movement, where students rallied to protect their language rights against governmental oppression.
name: Curzon Hall

detail_description: The Armenian Church Dhaka is a fascinating historical site that reflects the once thriving Armenian community in the city. Built in 1781, it stands as a testament to the community's existence and their refuge in Bengal to escape persecution. The church is located in Armanitola, an area named after the Armenian community that settled there. It was constructed on Armenian Street, donated by an individual of Armenian descent named Agaminus Catachik.
name: Armenian Church Dhaka
address: 4 Armenian Street, Armanitola Rd, Dhaka 1100, Bangladesh

detail_description: Ahsan Manzil, located near the Sadharghat Boat Terminal in Dhaka, is a must-visit destination. This magnificent structure was built by Nawab Abdul Gani, one of the city's wealthiest men. Ahsan Manzil stands as a testament to the opulence and grandeur of its time.
name: Ahsan Manzil

excerpt: 1800s palace of the Nawabs of Dhaka featuring an iconic pink facade, a dome & period furnishings.
detail_description: Ahsan Manzil Museum, also known as the Pink Palace, is a stunning 19th-century palace that served as the official residence of the Nawabs of Dhaka. This iconic pink palace showcases a blend of Mughal and European architectural styles, featuring a dome and period furnishings. Situated on the banks of the Buriganga River, it boasts a beautiful garden with lush greenery.
name: Ahsan Manzil Museum

excerpt: Large, tranquil green space with trees, formal gardens, paved walkways, a lake & a racecourse.
detail_description: Ramna Park, located in Dhaka, Bangladesh, is a vast 68-acre green space with trees, formal gardens, paved walkways, and a lake. Originally a Mughal-era garden redesigned during the British colonial period in the 19th century, it is known for its diverse flora including palm, mango, and banyan trees. The park hosts cultural festivals, concerts, and outdoor movie screenings throughout the year.
name: Ramna Park

excerpt: Sprawling mosque complex with spacious interior courtyards, a soaring minaret & geometric archways.
detail_description: Baitul Mukarram National Mosque, located in Dhaka, Bangladesh, is a significant landmark due to its size and unique design. It can accommodate up to 30,000 people and is among the top-10 largest mosques globally. Unlike traditional mosques, it features a cubic shape reminiscent of the Kasbah in Mecca and lacks some typical elements like minarets. The mosque's futuristic white exterior with rocket-like minarets makes it an iconic sight in Gulshan.
name: Baitul Mukarram National Mosque

detail_description: The Bangladesh National Parliament House, also known as Jatiya Sangsad Bhaban, is a remarkable legislative complex located in Dhaka. Designed by renowned architect Louis Kahn, this octagonal building stands as a symbol of the country's democracy and independence. Its unique modernist design incorporates elements of Bangladesh's heritage and has been hailed as an architectural masterpiece.
name: Bangladesh National Parliament House

excerpt: Kawran Bazar, misspelled as Karwan Bazar, is a central business district and is one of the biggest commodity marketplaces in Dhaka city, the capital of Bangladesh. Located in Tejgaon Thana, it is a designated commercial area of the Dhaka North City Corporation. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Kawran Bazar, also known as Karwan Bazar, is a bustling commercial district and the largest wholesale market in Dhaka, Bangladesh. It's a hub of diverse activities and an essential destination for photographers. The market operates from 12 PM to 9 AM, with some shops open throughout the day. Established by Marwari merchant Kawran Singh in the late 18th century, it supplies various goods like vegetables, fish, and rice to smaller markets.
name: Kawran Bazar

excerpt: Islamic prayer hall on an elevated platform from the 1700s, with three domes & a large courtyard.
detail_description: Khan Mohammad Mridha Masjid, located in Dhaka, is a historic Islamic prayer hall dating back to the 1700s. The mosque features a unique architectural style with three domes and a large courtyard. Constructed by Khan Muhammad Mridha, the site has been reasonably well restored, offering insight into religious practices and architectural trends of late 17th and early 18th century Dhaka.
name: Khan Mohammad Mridha Masjid

excerpt: National memorial dedicated to Bengali Language Movement activists killed during protests in 1952.
detail_description: Central Shaheed Minar, situated in Dhaka, Bangladesh, is a national monument dedicated to the activists who lost their lives during the Bengali Language Movement protests in 1952. This movement was a significant event in the country's history and arose from the demand for official status for the Bengali language. The monument stands as a tribute to those who were killed during this pivotal moment and serves as a reminder of their sacrifice for linguistic rights.
name: Central Shaheed Minar
address: Near Dhaka Medical College Gate, Secretariat Road, Secretariate Rd, Dhaka 1000, Bangladesh

excerpt: A lively area of narrow streets crammed with cycle rickshaws, Sadarghat is known for its bustling river port and boat trips along the Buriganga. Textbooks and discounted volumes, plus stationery, are for sale at Banglabazar Book Market, while Shankhari Bazar Road is dotted with Hindu temples and stores selling conch shell crafts, spices, and textiles. Casual eateries serve mutton dishes and other traditional fare.
detail_description: Sadarghat is a vibrant area filled with narrow streets bustling with cycle rickshaws and known for its lively river port and boat trips along the Buriganga. Visitors can explore the Banglabazar Book Market for discounted volumes and stationery, while Shankhari Bazar Road offers Hindu temples, conch shell crafts, spices, and textiles. The area also features casual eateries serving traditional mutton dishes.
name: Sadarghat

excerpt: Acclaimed, 210+ acre botanical garden, with a variety of plant life in Zen-like surroundings.
detail_description: The National Botanical Garden, situated in Mirpur-2, Dhaka, is a sprawling 210+ acre plant conservation center and tourist destination. It offers a serene environment with diverse plant life and beautiful flowers. The garden serves as a knowledge hub for nature enthusiasts and botanists. Additionally, it features the Buddha Garden in the Wari area of Dhaka as an administrative part of the National Park.
name: National Botanical Garden

excerpt: Large city zoo with a variety of native & non-native animals, elephant rides & a fishing lake.
detail_description: The Bangladesh National Zoo, also known as Mirpur Zoo, is a sprawling oasis in the Mirpur area of Dhaka. Spanning 186 acres, it houses a diverse collection of native and non-native animals, including Bengal tigers, African lions, and elephants. Visitors can enjoy elephant rides and explore colorful bird species. The zoo offers an educational experience on wildlife conservation and is popular among families during Eid and vacation times.
name: Bangladesh National Zoo

detail_description: Sadarghat River Port is a vibrant hub that truly encapsulates the essence of Dhaka. As one of the largest river ports globally, it buzzes with life, accommodating around 30,000 travelers daily. This bustling port serves as a gateway for various vessels including paddleboats and ferries navigating the Buriganga River. It's an ideal location for photographers eager to capture the dynamic scenes of local life and the constant movement of boats transporting people across southern Bangladesh.
name: Dhaka River Port

excerpt: A lake surrounds this huge, 20th-century legislative complex with unique modern architecture.
detail_description: The Parliament Building, designed by architect Louis Kahn, is a renowned architectural masterpiece located in Bangladesh. Originally commissioned to serve as the national parliament of East Pakistan, it is celebrated as one of the world's most exceptional structures.
name: Bangladesh National Parliament House

detail_description: Ahsan Manzil, also known as the Pink Palace, is a historical building located in Dhaka, Bangladesh. It was the official residential palace and seat of the Nawab of Dhaka. The palace is an architectural marvel, blending Mughal and European styles. Its pink facade and grand dome make it a striking sight. The interior is adorned with beautiful chandeliers, handcrafted furniture, and intricate decorations.
name: Ahsan Manzil

detail_description: Hatirjheel Bridge is a picturesque lakefront area situated in Dhaka, the vibrant capital of Bangladesh. This popular entertainment spot was transformed from a former slum area by the Bangladesh Army and Special Operations Forces in 2009. Today, it offers a serene escape for locals and visitors alike to enjoy leisurely strolls and recreational activities along its scenic waterfront.
name: Hatirjheel Bridge
address: Hatir Jheel Link Rd, Dhaka 1212, Bangladesh

excerpt: Dhaka is the capital city of Bangladesh, in southern Asia. Set beside the Buriganga River, its at the center of national government, trade and culture. The 17th-century old city was the Mughal capital of Bengal, and many palaces and mosques remain. American architect Louis Khans National Parliament House complex typifies the huge, fast-growing modern metropolis.
detail_description: Dhaka, the capital city of Bangladesh, is located in southern Asia and is a hub for national government, trade, and culture. The city's rich history as the 17th-century Mughal capital of Bengal is evident through its many remaining palaces and mosques. Additionally, Dhaka has rapidly grown into a modern metropolis with architectural marvels like the National Parliament House complex designed by American architect Louis Khan.
name: Dhaka

excerpt: Simple urban park area featuring a small pond & circular path for walking & running.
detail_description: Nestled in the upscale Gulshan district of Dhaka, Gulshan Society Lake Park is a delightful urban oasis that offers a peaceful retreat from the city's hustle and bustle. Spanning approximately 12 hectares, this well-maintained park features a picturesque lake surrounded by scenic walking and jogging paths. It's an ideal spot for locals and visitors alike to unwind, enjoy leisurely strolls, or engage in invigorating runs while soaking up the serene atmosphere.
name: Gulshan Society Lake Park

excerpt: Tranquil, spacious botanical gardens, founded in 1909, featuring plants from around the world.
detail_description: Baldha Garden, located in the heart of Dhaka, is a serene botanical garden established in 1909 by Narendra Narayan Roy Chowdhury. Spanning over 3.15 acres, it boasts a diverse collection of indigenous and exotic plants from around the world. The garden is a tranquil oasis amidst the bustling city, offering visitors a peaceful retreat to explore its rich variety of trees and vibrant birdlife.
name: Baldha Garden

detail_description: The Bangabandhu Military Museum, named after the Father of the Nation, Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, is a tribute to Bangladesh's military history and its liberation war. Located in Dhaka's Bijoy Sarani, it houses a diverse collection of military artifacts and exhibits that depict the bravery and sacrifices of the Bangladeshi armed forces throughout history, particularly during the 1971 Liberation War.
name: Bangabandhu Military Museum

detail_description: The University of Dhaka, established in 1921, is the oldest university in modern Bangladesh. It holds historical significance as it was the site where students and activists were killed during a protest for official status for their mother tongue, leading to the recognition of International Mother Language Day. The campus features notable landmarks like Curzon Hall, Jagannath Hall, Kazi Nazrul Islam's tomb, and Bhasa Shahid Minar.
name: University of Dhaka

detail_description: Sadarghat, also known as Sadarghat Port, is a bustling river port located in Dhaka. It is renowned as one of the largest river ports globally, witnessing a daily influx of over a hundred thousand travelers. The vibrant atmosphere at Sadarghat offers an authentic glimpse into the lively essence of Dhaka. Despite its chaotic nature, visitors can find solace in the oddly poetic experience of witnessing the sunset from this dynamic location.
name: Sadarghat

excerpt: Outdoor collection of rockets & painted airplanes, many of which can be entered, plus a play area.
detail_description: Nestled in the vibrant Sher-e-Bangla Nagar area of Dhaka, the Bangladesh Air Force Museum is a captivating destination for aviation enthusiasts and families alike. Opened to the public in October 2014, this museum showcases an impressive array of retired aircraft and military equipment that played crucial roles during Bangladesh's Liberation War. Visitors can explore various painted airplanes and rockets, many of which are accessible for a closer look.
name: Bangladesh Air Force Museum

excerpt: This historic 18th-century mosque features star patterns on its domes & tiled walls.
detail_description: Tara Masjid, an ancient mosque from the 18th century, displays intricate star designs on its domes and walls adorned with tiles. This historical landmark boasts of unique patterns that embellish its architectural beauty. The mosque is a testament to the exquisite craftsmanship of its time, evident in every corner of its structure. Tara Masjid's magnificent dome and ornamented walls are a sight to behold for anyone who appreciates art and history.
name: Tara Masjid

excerpt: Educational center with kid-friendly exhibits & galleries on physics, biology, space & technology.
detail_description: The National Museum of Science and Technology in Dhaka, Bangladesh is a significant establishment that highlights the country's scientific accomplishments and technological progress. Since its establishment in 1965, the museum has aimed to promote scientific education and foster innovation among the people of Bangladesh. Situated in the capital city, it features multiple floors with exhibits covering various aspects of science, technology, and innovation.
name: National Museum of Science and Technology

excerpt: Sizable city green space featuring a lake, walking paths, sports facilities & food stalls.
name: Dhanmondi Lake

detail_description: Bara Katra, also known as the Great Caravanserai, is a significant historical and architectural monument located in Dhaka. Built between 1644 and 1646 on the banks of the Buriganga River, it was originally intended to be the residence of Mughal prince Shah Shuja but later served as a guest house. The term "Katra" is believed to have originated from an Arabic word meaning a colonnaded building or caravanserai.
name: Bara Katra

excerpt: Planetarium offering virtual reality shows, educational lectures & space films in a 5D cinema.
detail_description: The Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Novo Theatre is a planetarium that offers virtual reality shows, educational lectures, and space films in a 5D cinema. It has recently undergone improvements, such as the addition of the Bangabandhu Corner, playground for children, and Nuclear Power Information Centre. The interior design is impressive with an adequate amount of space for visitors to enjoy watching 3D and 5D movies.
name: Novotheatre

excerpt: Venerable museum, established in 1913, displaying exhibits dedicated to Bengali history & culture.
detail_description: The Father of The Nation Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Memorial Museum is a poignant tribute to the charismatic leader who played a pivotal role in Bangladesh's independence. The museum is located in the former residence of Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, where he was arrested in 1971 and tragically assassinated along with his family in 1975. After years of military administration, the mansion was transformed into a museum in 1994 to honor his memory and legacy.
name: Father of The Nation Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Memorial Museum

excerpt: Heritage center for displays of Bangladeshi folk art, contemporary work & traditional dance shows.
detail_description: The Bangladesh Shilpakala Academy (BSA) is a national arts academy in Dhaka, established in 1974 to promote and develop the country's fine and performing arts. It serves as a heritage center for displaying Bangladeshi folk art, contemporary work, and traditional dance shows.
name: Bangladesh Shilpakala Academy

excerpt: Lively Old Dhaka is known for historic buildings like the Mughal-era Lalbagh Fort, set amid green lawns, and Dhakeshwari Mandir, a 12th-century Hindu temple. Period furnishings are on display at the Ahsan Manzil Museum, a vast palace with a pink facade. Street vendors sell breads and sweets, while Shankhari Bazar is a popular spot to find bangles, spices, and textiles. River boat trips depart from the Sadarghat area.
name: Old Dhaka

excerpt: Massive, multilevel retail center with 19 floors of stores & restaurants, plus a cinema & arcade.
detail_description: Bashundhara City Shopping Complex is a massive retail center located in Dhaka, Bangladesh. It is renowned as the largest shopping mall in South Asia and features 19 floors of stores, restaurants, a cinema, and an arcade. The complex offers a diverse range of shopping options including branded outlets for electronics, clothing, jewelry, and more. Visitors can also enjoy various entertainment zones such as Toggi Fun Worlds play zone for kids and riders.
name: Bashundhara City Shopping Complex
address: 3 No Tejturi Bazar West, Panthapath, Dhaka 1215, Bangladesh

detail_description: Rose Garden Palace, originally built by Hindu landlord Hrishikesh Das in the 19th century as a place for entertainment, holds historical significance as the birthplace of the Awami League. In 2018, the government acquired this property for Tk 331.70 crore due to its archaeological value, preserving its rich heritage and cultural importance.
name: Rose Garden Palace
address: K. M. Dash Ln, Dhaka, Bangladesh

name: Mausoleum of Three Leaders
address: P9HX+JXV, Suhrawardi Udyan Rd, Dhaka 1000, Bangladesh

detail_description: Jatiyo Sangsad Bhaban, also known as the National Parliament House in Dhaka, is a remarkable architectural marvel in Bangladesh. Designed by the renowned American architect Louis Khan, it stands as one of the most significant landmarks in the country. Situated at Sher-e Bangla Nagar, this expansive legislative complex is celebrated as the largest of its kind globally.
name: Jatiyo Sangsad Bhaban

detail_description: New Market - Pilkhana Rd is a must-visit destination for those looking to experience the vibrant shopping scene in Bangladesh. Here, visitors can find world-renowned clothing brands at incredibly affordable prices, making it a paradise for bargain hunters.
name: New Market - Pilkhana Rd

detail_description: When exploring Dhaka, the National Parliament House is an absolute must-see. This architectural marvel, crafted by the legendary Louis Kahn, offers a stunning visual experience that goes beyond mere structure. Nestled amidst serene lakes and striking geometric designs, it stands as one of the largest legislative complexes globally. The area around Gate No. 5 is particularly tranquil and well-maintained, making it a perfect spot for reflection and appreciation of this iconic landmark.
name: 6 No Gate, National Parliament House

excerpt: Bangladesh, to the east of India on the Bay of Bengal, is a South Asian country marked by lush greenery and many waterways. Its Padma (Ganges), Meghna and Jamuna rivers create fertile plains, and travel by boat is common. On the southern coast, the Sundarbans, an enormous mangrove forest shared with Eastern India, is home to the royal Bengal tiger.
name: Bangladesh

detail_description: The National Art Gallery in Segun Bagicha, Dhaka, is a cultural treasure established by the Shilpakala Academy. Since its inception in 1974, it has gained recognition for its impressive architecture and multi-storied layout. The gallery features works by esteemed national artists like Zainul Abedin and Quamrul Hassan. It also serves as an educational hub where students learn art preservation techniques.
name: National Art Gallery ~ SegunBagicha

detail_description: The Buriganga River flows through Dhaka, the capital city of Bangladesh, and plays a significant role in the economic, cultural, and political aspects of the country. The river is home to the bustling Sadarghat Port, one of the world's largest river ports where thousands of people commute daily. Despite its pollution issues, taking a boat journey on the Buriganga offers a refreshing experience amidst nature. Additionally, it serves as an essential transportation route for millions of people.
name: Buriganga River

excerpt: Lalbagh is a neighbourhood of the Dhaka District in the division of Dhaka, Bangladesh. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Lalbagh, located in the Dhaka District of Bangladesh, is a vibrant neighborhood within the division of Dhaka. It offers a blend of modern urban living and traditional Bangladeshi culture, making it an intriguing destination for visitors looking to immerse themselves in local life.
name: Lalbagh

detail_description: The Taka Museum, situated in Dhaka, the capital city of Bangladesh, serves as the central bank of the country and holds responsibility for issuing the national currency known as Bangladeshi taka. Established in 2010, this museum boasts an extensive collection of taka notes and coins from various historical periods. It offers a remarkable opportunity to explore and acquire knowledge about banknotes and coins. In addition to displaying Bangladeshi taka currency, it also showcases currencies from other nations.
name: Taka Museum
address: 1stFloor, Bangladesh Bank Training Academy, 5 Mirpur Rd, Dhaka 1216, Bangladesh

excerpt: Mellow store featuring a wide variety of books on quirky displays, plus a cafe with drinks & sweets.
detail_description: Bengal Boi, located in Dhanmondi, Dhaka, is a renowned bookstore cafe that has been championing reading since 2017. The cozy and inviting ambiance offers a diverse selection of books and magazines displayed in quirky setups. It's an ideal spot for book lovers to discover new authors or delve into Bangladeshi literature. The store also features a cafe where visitors can enjoy refreshing tea or grab a light snack while reading or chatting with friends.
name: Bengal Boi ~ Dhanmondi
